parameters.content:
## Dynamically Replace Images in Google Slides
This workflow exposes an API endpoint that lets you dynamically replace an image in Google Slides, perfect for automating deck presentations like updating backgrounds or client logos.

### Step 1: Set Up a Key Identifier in Google Slides
Add a unique key identifier to the images you want to replace.
1. Click on the image.
2. Go to **Format Options** and then **Alt Text**.
3. Enter your unique identifier, like `client_logo` or `background`.

### Step 2: Use a POST Request to Update the Image
Send a POST request to the workflow endpoint with the following parameters in the body:
- `presentation_id`: The ID of your Google Slides presentation.
You can find it in the URL of your Google presentation : `https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/{this-part}/edit#slide=id.p`)
- `image_key`: The unique identifier you created.
- `image_url`: The URL of the new image.

That's it! The specified image in your Google Slides presentation will be replaced with the new one from the provided URL.

This workflow is designed to be flexible, allowing you to use the same identifier across multiple slides and presentations. I hope it streamlines your slide automation process!

Happy automating!
The n8Ninja

How to Properly Wash Hands (at least 20-30 seconds)
Use running water as hot as you can comfortably stand.
Scrub hands and arms vigorously for 10-15 seconds.
Preferably clean, short fingernails (Nail polish is okay with gloves.)
Take off all rings, bracelets, or watches before beginning to serve food. (Plain bands are okay with wear.)
For the ladies (and certain guys), please tie up your hair.
If possible, when serving, please wear closed toed shoes.
If you get a cut on your hand, please ask someone to cover you while you bandage the wound. Always wear gloves over the bandage if you are continuing to serve food.
If you are sick/feeling like you will get sick, PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE get someone on the Food Team to substitute for you.
Use separate tongs, spoons, or other serving utensils when serving each item to prevent cross contamination.
When holding dish plates, hold them by the bottom or edge.
Major food allergies: milk, eggs, fish, shellfish, wheat, soy, peanuts, tree nuts
PLEASE let the team know if there is a food allergy that we are unaware of by telling us and putting it on the dietary preferences Google Doc.
Wash and dry your hands before putting on gloves
Do not roll gloves to make them easier to put on
As soon as gloves get dirty or torn
After an interruption such as taking a phone call
Do not let catered food stay out longer than 4 hours due to bacterial growth.
All food trays and supplies should be placed at least 6” off the ground.
When serving food, please use the First In, First Out (or FIFO) method.
Wash serving utensils and equipment with detergent and air dry. Place utensils in clean container.
Replace serving utensils if too worn or chipped. Chipped or cracked surfaces may carry unwanted bacteria.
Clean and organize storage containers periodically. Helps for inventory purposes too
Budget of average $200 weekly (some weeks over budget is ok) starting 2023
Do not repeat items on consecutive services
Find shops around your team’s area to try
Church volunteers (non team members) serving in 2023
Set up tables (if they aren’t already) in front of the lockers in the courtyard on the gym side.
No need to tear down tables afterwards
Either give away leftovers, take home, or throw away
Set up outside, not at the concession stand (for now)
Wen Coffee Hour? (Wen early wake up?)
When Rayson figures out when he wants to and how to execute.
No space in van for tea box and water heater.
Up to coffee boys if they want to provide tea or if anyone in Food Team wants to bring it on their week.
Planning Team + Day-Of Team, each team rotates turns within itself
Planning Team plans and orders; Day-Of Team picks up and serves the food
Hosted in Cafeteria with courtyard as overflow
